04499nam a22006735i 9781487532802DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202019onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875328027 a10.3138/97814875328022doi  a(DE-B1597)540142  a(OCoLC)1143819683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aJN5269b.C613 2020 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a320.09453112231 aContarini, Gasparo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Republic of Venice :bDe magistratibus et republica Venetorum /cGasparo Contarini; ed. by Filippo Sabetti. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLorenzo Da Ponte Italian Library00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Gasparo Contarini and Enduring Institutions -- tAppendix A: The Myth and Anti-myth of Venice -- tAppendix B: Glossary of Terms -- tAppendix C: Principal Events in Gasparo Contarini’s Life -- tNotes on the Translation: The Latin of De magistratibus et republica Venetorum -- tTHE REPUBLIC OF VENICE -- tBook 1. The City and the Great Council -- tBook 2. The Doge -- tBook 3. The Senate, the Council of Ten, and the Courts -- tBook 4. Magistracies of the Republic -- tBook 5. Magistracies beyond the City, the Army, and Civic Institutions -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when social scientists are increasingly focusing on the reasons why nations fail and democracies die, Filippo Sabetti turns to the opposite argument, asking instead why institutions endure. To do so, he presents Gasparo Contarini’s sixteenth-century account of the Republic of Venice to help modern readers understand what made Venice the longest-lived self-constituted republic. In its long history, Venice was the only city that succeeded in constructing a durable republicanism and it was one of the earliest to depart from the hierarchical world of national monarchies and sovereignty. Because of this, the author suggests that Contarini’s The Republic of Venice may be just as instructive, if not more, than Machiavelli’s The Prince to students of politics. Contarini is as secular as Machiavelli and is as realistic in his view of human nature, but he goes much further, examining in the case of Venice how it is possible for fallible human beings to construct a successful and stable government. This is the first modern English-language edition of Contarini’s classic work, De magistratibus et republica Venetorum, from the original Latin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aMachiavelli.  aRenaissance.  aThe Prince.  aVenice.  aconstitutionalism.  aenduring institutions.  ahistory of political science.  amechanisms of collective action.  arepublic.  asocial capital.1 aMurphy, Amanda.1 aPezzini, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPezzini, Giuseppe.1 aSabetti, Filippo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSabetti, Filippo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753280240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532802423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487532802.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles